00:04:07.112 --> 00:04:08.881
<i> of Alzheimer's disease.</i>

00:04:08.981 --> 00:04:11.117
<i> Wingo and his team
 looked at the risk</i>

00:04:11.217 --> 00:04:14.086 align:start size:91% position:9%
<i> of Alzheimer's disease
 among parents and children</i>

00:04:14.186 --> 00:04:16.956 align:start size:75% position:25%
<i> in 702 people
 with young onset.</i>

00:04:17.056 --> 00:04:19.592 align:start size:91% position:9% line:83%
<i> From 32 Alzheimer's disease
 research centers</i>

00:04:19.692 --> 00:04:21.026 line:85%
<i> across the country.</i>

00:04:21.126 --> 00:04:24.196 line:83%
<i> They compared them
 to over 5,000 people</i>

00:04:24.296 --> 00:04:26.499 line:85%
<i> with late onset Alzheimer's.</i>

00:04:26.599 --> 00:04:28.067
It really surprised us.

00:04:28.167 --> 00:04:29.902 align:start size:94% position:6%
<i> (Jaye Watson)
 What surprised Wingo was that</i>

00:04:30.002 --> 00:04:32.805 line:76%
<i> among the 702 people
 with young onset,</i>

00:04:32.905 --> 00:04:35.341 align:start size:56% position:44%
<i> only between four
 and eight percent</i>

00:04:35.441 --> 00:04:36.809 align:start size:56% position:44%
<i> had a parent with
 young onset</i>

00:04:36.909 --> 00:04:38.611 align:start size:66% position:34%
<i> Alzheimer's disease.</i>

00:04:38.711 --> 00:04:41.780 align:start size:91% position:9%
<i> But when they looked at
 siblings of those patients,</i>

00:04:41.880 --> 00:04:46.085 align:start size:88% position:13% line:76%
<i> almost 22% of them
 had young onset as well.</i>

00:04:46.185 --> 00:04:50.022 align:start size:94% position:6%
<i> How is it possible in
 families with healthy parents</i>

00:04:50.122 --> 00:04:52.959
<i> that more children
 wind up with it?</i>

00:04:53.059 --> 00:04:55.094 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> (Wingo)
 We were surprised to find
 that the data suggested</i>

00:04:55.194 --> 00:04:57.897
<i> that parents who were fine,</i>

00:04:57.997 --> 00:05:02.101 line:83%
