of a defective gene,

00:05:02.201 --> 00:05:04.136 align:start size:88% position:13% line:83%
but when--
and they passed it along

00:05:04.236 --> 00:05:06.105 align:start size:81% position:19% line:83%
to a child that
inherited two copies

00:05:06.205 --> 00:05:07.974 line:85%
of this defective gene.

00:05:08.074 --> 00:05:11.643 align:start size:91% position:9%
<i> (Jaye Watson)
 Wingo's Autosomal
 Recessive Hypothesis means</i>

00:05:11.743 --> 00:05:14.747 align:start size:94% position:6%
<i> each parent would have
 a defective copy, or copies,</i>

00:05:14.847 --> 00:05:16.215
<i> of a family of genes.</i>

00:05:16.316 --> 00:05:19.685 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> That defective copy from
 each parent creates</i>

00:05:19.785 --> 00:05:21.187
<i> young onset in
 their children</i>

00:05:21.287 --> 00:05:23.589
<i> who inherit both copies.</i>

00:05:23.689 --> 00:05:26.458 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> It's like a bad luck
 lottery for two parents</i>

00:05:26.558 --> 00:05:29.495 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> to have copies of this
 defective gene.</i>

00:05:29.595 --> 00:05:31.063
These mutations, um,

00:05:31.163 --> 00:05:33.633
would have to be very rare
in the general population.

00:05:33.733 --> 00:05:35.467
Say like 1% frequency.

00:05:35.567 --> 00:05:37.637 align:start size:78% position:22%
Certainly less
than 5% frequency.

00:05:37.737 --> 00:05:41.807 align:start size:75% position:25%
<i> (Jaye Watson)
 The human body
 has 20,500 genes.</i>

00:05:41.907 --> 00:05:45.344 align:start size:97% position:3%
<i> Wingo and his team don't
 know the precise ones involved</i>

00:05:45.444 --> 00:05:47.880 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> but have narrowed
