00:18:28.373 --> 00:18:29.574 align:start size:75% position:25%
<i> One in which
 typical children</i>

00:18:29.674 --> 00:18:32.210 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> and children with autism
 are together.</i>

00:18:32.311 --> 00:18:35.447 align:start size:81% position:19%
<i> The curriculum mixes
 developmental brain
 science research</i>

00:18:35.547 --> 00:18:37.615 align:start size:81% position:19%
<i> with early
 education practices.</i>

00:18:37.715 --> 00:18:41.753
<i>It's mixed into a day filled
with what children want to do--</i>

00:18:41.853 --> 00:18:44.022
<i> play and learn.</i>

00:18:44.122 --> 00:18:46.625
<i> Decades of research has
 shown that having models,</i>

00:18:46.725 --> 00:18:49.361 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> typical kids, to imitate
 and learn from,</i>

00:18:49.461 --> 00:18:53.131 align:start size:91% position:9%
<i> actually changes the brains
 of children with autism.</i>

00:18:53.231 --> 00:18:55.200 line:83%
And with that, it is
changing the brain

00:18:55.300 --> 00:18:57.702 line:83%
and developing new
neural pathways.

00:18:57.802 --> 00:19:01.006 align:start size:94% position:6% line:83%
Or changing neural pathways,
so that they're learning

00:19:01.106 --> 00:19:04.209 align:start size:91% position:9% line:83%
to compensate for those
deficits due to the autism,

00:19:04.309 --> 00:19:06.111 align:start size:81% position:19% line:83%
they're learning how
to make those up

00:19:06.211 --> 00:19:08.746 align:start size:94% position:6% line:83%
and how to really get normal
social interactions.

00:19:08.847 --> 00:19:10.582 line:83%
Normal language
development.

00:19:10.682 --> 00:19:12.617 align:start size:78% position:22%
(Jaye Watson)
This exposure to
incidental learning

00:19:12.717 --> 00:19:14.653 align:start size:75% position:25%
can lead to
profound results.

00:19:14.753 --> 00:19:17.088 line:83%
About a third of children
with autism can eventually

00:19:17.188 --> 00:19:20.258 align:start size:88% position:13% line:83%
become indistinguishable
from their peers.

00:19:20.359 --> 00:19:23.795 line:83%
With abilities to have
meaningful relationships.

00:19:23.895 --> 00:19:26.064 align:start size:78% position:22% line:83%
For Amiel and Elise
it was simple,

00:19:26.164 --> 00:19:27.432
they liked each other.

00:19:27.532 --> 00:19:30.969 align:start size:56% position:44%
She liked me the
first time we met.

00:19:31.069 --> 00:19:32.871 align:start size:50% position:50%
I think we liked
each other.

00:19:32.971 --> 00:19:34.539 align:start size:78% position:22%
I think the first time we
met, we started to play

00:19:34.639 --> 00:19:36.040 align:start size:72% position:28%
with each other, right?

00:19:36.140 --> 00:19:38.576 align:start position:0%
Yeah.

00:19:38.676 --> 00:19:40.912 align:start size:56% position:44%
I don't know what
day it was since--

00:19:41.012 --> 00:19:42.947 align:start size:56% position:44%
We forgot what day
it was, right?

00:19:43.047 --> 00:19:44.716 align:start size:72% position:28%
Could've been a Monday.

00:19:44.816 --> 00:19:47.119
<i> (collective chatter)</i>

00:19:47.219 --> 00:19:48.120 align:start size:53% position:47%
<i> I was thinking
 it's been awhile</i>

00:19:48.220 --> 00:19:49.655 align:start size:59% position:41%
<i> since they've been
 to the park, um--</i>

00:19:49.755 --> 00:19:50.421 size:75% position:38%
Yeah, we should do that.

00:19:50.521 --> 00:19:51.923 align:start size:50% position:50%
But they do lots
of playdates.

00:19:52.023 --> 00:19:53.258 align:start position:0% line:83%
Yeah, yeah, we've gone to
the park together.

00:19:52.023 --> 00:19:53.258 align:start size:81% position:19%
Yeah, yeah, several times.

00:19:53.358 --> 00:19:55.027 align:start size:78% position:22%
<i> (Jaye Watson)
 Amiel's mom Rachel</i>

00:19:55.127 --> 00:19:57.496 align:start size:84% position:16% line:83%
<i> says Elise is his first
 real friend.</i>

00:19:57.596 --> 00:19:59.764 align:start position:0% line:83%
They were connected from
like the first day.

00:19:59.864 --> 00:20:01.966
<i> Amiel began by being
 a good friend to Elise</i>

00:20:02.066 --> 00:20:03.935
<i> who was new last year.</i>

00:20:04.035 --> 00:20:05.604 align:start size:81% position:19% line:83%
I feel like he did a great
job of reaching out

00:20:05.704 --> 00:20:07.405 align:start size:75% position:25% line:85%
to her when she was new.

00:20:07.505 --> 00:20:08.273 align:start position:0% line:85%
That's so sweet.

00:20:08.373 --> 00:20:09.641 align:start size:63% position:38% line:83%
Yeah, and making
her feel comfortable

00:20:09.741 --> 00:20:11.710 align:start size:47% position:53% line:83%
and helping her
make friends.

00:20:11.810 --> 00:20:14.646 align:start position:0%
<i>There's an honesty that happens
in the best friendships.</i>

00:20:14.746 --> 00:20:18.250 align:start position:0%
<i>He goes wherever I go
because he likes me.</i>

00:20:18.350 --> 00:20:20.618 align:start size:75% position:25%
Well, sometimes I don't.

00:20:20.719 --> 00:20:23.721 align:start size:81% position:19%
<i> Friendships filled
 with bows and boasts.</i>

00:20:23.821 --> 00:20:26.791
"Nothing left to prove.
Nothing left to prove."

00:20:26.891 --> 00:20:28.926 align:start size:81% position:19%
<i> The research has
 shown something else.</i>

00:20:29.026 --> 00:20:32.730
<i> Typical kids benefit as much
 as the students with autism</i>

00:20:32.830 --> 00:20:34.866
<i> but in a different way.</i>

00:20:34.967 --> 00:20:37.368
Most of them are
more empathetic.

00:20:37.468 --> 00:20:41.539 align:start size:94% position:6%
They're not as noticing
of differences of other kids.

00:20:41.639 --> 00:20:45.443
They have a lot more
compassion for people

00:20:45.543 --> 00:20:47.845
<i> and the research shows
 that over and over again</i>

00:20:47.945 --> 00:20:49.481
<i> for inclusion in general,</i>

00:20:49.581 --> 00:20:50.748
<i> but especially when
 they're including</i>

00:20:50.848 --> 00:20:52.117
<i> the children with autism.</i>

00:20:52.217 --> 00:20:54.986 align:start size:81% position:19%
<i> (Jaye Watson)
 At four and a half
 and five and a half,</i>

00:20:55.087 --> 00:20:57.589 align:start size:88% position:13%
<i> these two teach us
 that despite differences,</i>

00:20:57.689 --> 00:21:02.160 align:start size:84% position:16%
<i> we can travel
 the same path together.</i>

00:21:02.260 --> 00:21:05.897 align:start size:63% position:38%
Um, she has me back.

00:21:05.997 --> 00:21:06.764 align:start size:63% position:38%
<i> (teacher)
 Go!</i>

00:21:06.865 --> 00:21:07.632
<i> Run, run!</i>

00:21:07.733 --> 00:21:10.535
(laughing)

00:21:11.403 --> 00:21:14.038 align:start size:91% position:9%
Kids don't see differences
the way we adults do.

00:21:14.138 --> 00:21:16.641 align:start size:84% position:16%
A brief trip on social
media these days

00:21:16.741 --> 00:21:18.977 align:start size:81% position:19%
shows you how divided
we can be.

00:21:19.077 --> 00:21:21.112 align:start size:91% position:9%
Which is why it's good
to remember a simple truth,

00:21:21.212 --> 00:21:22.914
we all want friends.

00:21:23.015 --> 00:21:27.218 align:start size:84% position:16%
We all want to feel
included and supported.

00:21:27.318 --> 00:21:30.722 align:start size:94% position:6%
In that way, Amiel and Elise
are teachers reminding us

00:21:30.822 --> 00:21:34.725 align:start size:91% position:9%
that embracing differences
opens doors and minds

00:21:34.826 --> 00:21:37.228
to friendship
and happiness.

00:21:37.328 --> 00:21:39.731
That's gonna do it
for us this week.

